  <archetypedescription>
    <p>
      <emph>
	So much has been done — more, far more, will I achieve: treading in the steps already marked,
	I will pioneer a new way, explore unknown powers, and unfold to the world the deepest mysteries
	of creation.
      </emph>
      The Late Heinrich Khunrath of Amburg (Immolated for Blasphemy in 1399).
    </p>
    
    <p>
      The Eternal Brotherhood, known commonly as the Plague Doctors are a small, mysterious,
      hermetic and esoteric brotherhood who pursue the mysteries of creation, and immortality.  They
      dedicate their lives to the study of the sciences,  magicks, and the workings of the worlds.
      The society is sworn to anonymity.  All members wear a mask in public and adopt a public pseudonym.
      Roll for your psuedonym using the table below (roll twice, once for the forename and once for the
      surname), or choose one of your own.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      The founding principles of the sect are laid out in two documents, the Fama Fraternitatis (the
      Report of the Brotherhood), and the Confessio Fraternitatis (the Confessions of the Brotherhood).
      These works were published under the psuedonym Großmütiger Adler, but are believed to have been
      authored by Philippus Aureolus Theophrastus Bombastus von Hohenheim.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      Plague Doctors tend to come from a financially independent background.  The middle and lower
      classes do not have the resources to throw themselves into a lifetime of study with little prospect
      of financial reward.  
    </p>
    
    <p>
      The foundations of the brotherhoods research centers on five main pillars: Biology,
      Electrochemistry, Blaylock Valves, Humoural Theory, and Leeches.  While the theories of
      Biology and Electrochemistry are known to a certain well-educated subset of society, the
      other three areas of research are almost entirely the province of the research of the
      brotherhood of Plague Doctors.  Many Plague Doctors keep appraised of the latest
      breakthroughs by subscribing to their research gazette, the Lance.
    </p>
    
